io.jsonwebtoken

Class Jwts

  • java.lang.Object
    • io.jsonwebtoken.Jwts

  • public final class Jwts
extends Object
    Factory class useful for creating instances of JWT interfaces. Using this factory class can be a good alternative to tightly coupling your code to implementation classes.
    Since:
    0.1

    • Method Summary

      All Methods Static Methods Concrete Methods 
      Modifier and Type Method and Description
      static JwtBuilder builder()
      Returns a new JwtBuilder instance that can be configured and then used to create JWT compact serialized strings.
      static Claims claims()
      Returns a new Claims instance to be used as a JWT body.
      static Claims claims(Map<String,Object> claims)
      Returns a new Claims instance populated with the specified name/value pairs.
      static Header header()
      Creates a new Header instance suitable for plaintext (not digitally signed) JWTs.
      static Header header(Map<String,Object> header)
      Creates a new Header instance suitable for plaintext (not digitally signed) JWTs, populated with the specified name/value pairs.

      Returns a new JwsHeader instance suitable for digitally signed JWTs (aka 'JWS's).

      Returns a new JwsHeader instance suitable for digitally signed JWTs (aka 'JWS's), populated with the specified name/value pairs.

    • Method Detail

      • header

        public static Header header()
        Creates a new Header instance suitable for plaintext (not digitally signed) JWTs. As this is a less common use of JWTs, consider using the jwsHeader() factory method instead if you will later digitally sign the JWT.
        Returns:
        a new Header instance suitable for plaintext (not digitally signed) JWTs.

      • header

        public static Header header(Map<String,Object> header)
        Creates a new Header instance suitable for plaintext (not digitally signed) JWTs, populated with the specified name/value pairs. As this is a less common use of JWTs, consider using the jwsHeader(java.util.Map) factory method instead if you will later digitally sign the JWT.
        Returns:
        a new Header instance suitable for plaintext (not digitally signed) JWTs.
